    # --- TEAMS ---
    {"id": "tm1", "text": "Manchester City under Pep Guardiola play a possession-based style with high defensive line, inverted wingers, and a false nine or striker. They press aggressively and recycle possession quickly. They have dominated the Premier League winning multiple consecutive titles."},
    {"id": "tm2", "text": "Liverpool under Jurgen Klopp became one of Europe's best teams through gegenpressing, direct vertical passing, and dynamic attacking play. Their front three of Salah, Mane, and Firmino was one of the most feared in world football. Klopp left in 2024."},
    {"id": "tm3", "text": "Arsenal under Mikel Arteta play an aggressive high press with quick combinations in tight spaces. They have challenged for the Premier League title in recent seasons after years of rebuilding. Their style emphasizes positional play and pressing triggers."},
    {"id": "tm4", "text": "Chelsea have undergone significant rebuilding under new ownership with massive investment in players. They have struggled for consistency despite spending heavily. Under various managers they have experimented with different systems."},
    {"id": "tm5", "text": "Tottenham Hotspur have historically been known for attractive attacking football. Under Antonio Conte they adopted a more pragmatic 3-4-3 system. After Conte's departure they have continued searching for a consistent identity."},
    {"id": "tm6", "text": "Newcastle United have been transformed since their Saudi-led takeover in 2021. Under Eddie Howe they play an energetic pressing style and have qualified for European football for the first time in decades, investing heavily in the squad."},
    {"id": "tm7", "text": "Aston Villa under Unai Emery have become one of the Premier League's most improved sides. Emery's tactical organization and squad development have taken Villa from relegation candidates to European contenders within two seasons."},
    {"id": "tm8", "text": "Real Madrid are one of the most successful clubs in football history, especially in the UEFA Champions League. They are known for elite mentality, world-class players, fast transitions, and the ability to win decisive knockout matches."},
    {"id": "tm9", "text": "Barcelona are famous for La Masia, possession football, and technical midfielders. Their modern identity was shaped by Johan Cruyff and later perfected under Pep Guardiola with players like Messi, Xavi, Iniesta, and Busquets."},
    {"id": "tm10", "text": "Bayern Munich are Germany's dominant club and are known for attacking football, strong physical players, and consistent success in the Bundesliga. They have also won multiple Champions League titles."},
    {"id": "tm11", "text": "Paris Saint-Germain became a European superclub after major investment from Qatar Sports Investments. They have dominated French football and attracted global stars such as Neymar, Mbappe, Messi, and Ibrahimovic."},
    {"id": "tm12", "text": "Borussia Dortmund are known for passionate fans, the Yellow Wall, attacking football, and developing young players. They have produced or developed stars such as Lewandowski, Haaland, Bellingham, and Sancho."},
    {"id": "tm13", "text": "Atletico Madrid under Diego Simeone became famous for defensive discipline, compact shape, counter-attacks, and emotional intensity. They have challenged Barcelona and Real Madrid despite smaller resources."},
    {"id": "tm14", "text": "Inter Milan are one of Italy's biggest clubs and have a history of strong defensive teams, tactical discipline, and success in Serie A and European competitions."},
    {"id": "tm15", "text": "AC Milan are one of Europe's most historic clubs, known for legendary defenders, midfielders, and Champions League success. The club has had iconic players such as Maldini, Kaka, Pirlo, and Shevchenko."},
    {"id": "tm16", "text": "Juventus are Italy's most successful domestic club, known for defensive organization, winning mentality, and long periods of Serie A dominance."},
    {"id": "tm17", "text": "Napoli became famous for attacking football and passionate support, especially during the Diego Maradona era and later during their Serie A title-winning campaign with players like Victor Osimhen and Khvicha Kvaratskhelia."},
    {"id": "tm18", "text": "Manchester United are one of the biggest clubs in world football. Their most successful period came under Sir Alex Ferguson, when they dominated English football and won multiple Premier League titles and Champions League trophies."},
    {"id": "tm19", "text": "West Ham United are known for their academy tradition, physical style, and passionate East London fanbase. They won the UEFA Europa Conference League in 2023."},
    {"id": "tm20", "text": "Brighton & Hove Albion became admired for smart recruitment, possession football, and developing undervalued players. Their data-driven model has helped them compete with richer Premier League clubs."},
    {"id": "tm21", "text": "Brentford are known for analytics-based recruitment, set-piece strength, and efficient squad building. They reached the Premier League with a modern data-focused approach."},
    {"id": "tm22", "text": "Leicester City shocked world football by winning the Premier League in 2015-16. Their title-winning team relied on compact defending, quick counter-attacks, Jamie Vardy's pace, and Riyad Mahrez's creativity."},

    # --- RULES ---
    {"id": "r1", "text": "The offside rule states a player is offside if they are nearer to the opponent's goal than both the ball and the second-to-last defender when the ball is played to them. Being offside is only an offense if the player is involved in active play."},
    {"id": "r2", "text": "VAR (Video Assistant Referee) was introduced to the Premier League in 2019. It reviews clear and obvious errors in four categories: goals, penalty decisions, direct red cards, and mistaken identity. The on-field referee can be advised to review incidents on a pitchside monitor."},
    {"id": "r3", "text": "A penalty kick is awarded when a foul or handball occurs inside the penalty area. It is taken from the penalty spot 12 yards from goal. All players except the taker and goalkeeper must be outside the penalty area until the ball is kicked."},
    {"id": "r4", "text": "The handball rule states that it is an offense if a player deliberately handles the ball. Goals scored with the hand or arm are disallowed. Unintentional handball can still be penalized if it leads directly to a goal or goal-scoring opportunity."},
    {"id": "r5", "text": "A red card results in immediate dismissal from the match. A player receives a red card for violent conduct, serious foul play, spitting, denying a clear goal-scoring opportunity, or receiving two yellow cards in the same match. The team plays with ten men for the remainder of the game."},
    {"id": "r6", "text": "A yellow card is a caution given by the referee for misconduct such as reckless tackles, dissent, time wasting, or stopping a promising attack. Two yellow cards in the same match result in a red card."},
    {"id": "r7", "text": "Added time is extra time added at the end of each half to compensate for stoppages such as injuries, substitutions, VAR checks, goal celebrations, and time wasting."},
    {"id": "r8", "text": "A free kick is awarded after a foul or rule violation. Direct free kicks can be shot straight into the goal, while indirect free kicks must touch another player before a goal can count."},
    {"id": "r9", "text": "A corner kick is awarded when the defending team last touches the ball before it crosses their own goal line without a goal being scored. Corners are important attacking set-piece opportunities."},
    {"id": "r10", "text": "A goal kick is awarded when the attacking team last touches the ball before it crosses the defending team's goal line without a goal being scored. The defending team restarts play from inside the goal area."},
    {"id": "r11", "text": "A throw-in is awarded when the ball fully crosses the touchline. The player taking the throw must use both hands, throw from behind and over the head, and keep both feet on or behind the touchline."},
    {"id": "r12", "text": "A foul is an unfair action such as tripping, pushing, holding, charging recklessly, or kicking an opponent. Fouls can result in free kicks, penalties, yellow cards, or red cards depending on severity and location."},
    {"id": "r13", "text": "Advantage is when the referee allows play to continue after a foul because the fouled team still has a promising attacking situation. If the advantage does not develop, the referee may bring play back."},
    {"id": "r14", "text": "A substitution allows a team to replace one player with another during a match. Modern competitions usually allow five substitutions, though the exact number can depend on the competition rules."},
    {"id": "r15", "text": "A player is considered in active play for offside if they interfere with play, interfere with an opponent, or gain an advantage from their position. Simply standing in an offside position is not automatically an offense."},
    {"id": "r16", "text": "Denial of an obvious goal-scoring opportunity, often called DOGSO, can result in a red card if a player illegally prevents an opponent from having a clear chance to score."},
    {"id": "r17", "text": "Serious foul play involves a challenge that endangers the safety of an opponent. It is usually punished with a red card."},
    {"id": "r18", "text": "Violent conduct refers to aggressive behavior away from a legitimate attempt to play the ball, such as striking or elbowing an opponent. It is punished with a red card."},
    {"id": "r19", "text": "The captain has no special rule-making power but is often the main player who communicates with the referee. Captains lead teammates, organize behavior, and represent the team during key moments."},
    {"id": "r20", "text": "The goalkeeper is the only player allowed to handle the ball, but only inside their own penalty area. Outside the box, the goalkeeper is treated like any other outfield player."},
    
    
    # --- COMPETITIONS ---
    {"id": "c1", "text": "The Premier League was founded in 1992 when the top clubs broke away from the Football League. It consists of 20 clubs playing 38 matches each season. Manchester United have won it the most times with 13 titles since its formation. It is the most watched football league in the world."},
    {"id": "c2", "text": "The UEFA Champions League is Europe's premier club competition. It features the top clubs from each European league competing in a group stage followed by knockout rounds. The final is one of the most watched sporting events globally."},
    {"id": "c3", "text": "The FA Cup is the oldest football competition in the world, founded in 1871. It is a knockout tournament open to all clubs in the English football pyramid. It is known for potential giant-killing upsets where lower league clubs defeat top flight teams."},
    {"id": "c4", "text": "La Liga is Spain's top football division and has historically been dominated by Real Madrid and Barcelona. It is known for technical football, elite midfielders, and world-class attacking players."},
    {"id": "c5", "text": "Serie A is Italy's top football league and is known for tactical sophistication, defensive organization, and historic clubs such as Juventus, Inter Milan, AC Milan, Roma, Lazio, and Napoli."},
    {"id": "c6", "text": "The Bundesliga is Germany's top football league and is known for high attendances, intense pressing, attacking football, and strong fan culture. Bayern Munich have dominated the competition for long periods."},
    {"id": "c7", "text": "Ligue 1 is France's top football division. It has produced many talented young players and has been dominated in recent years by Paris Saint-Germain."},
    {"id": "c8", "text": "The UEFA Europa League is Europe's second-tier club competition. It features strong clubs from across Europe and often provides a route into the Champions League for the winner."},
    {"id": "c9", "text": "The UEFA Europa Conference League is Europe's third-tier club competition. It gives more clubs from smaller leagues the chance to compete in European knockout football."},
    {"id": "c10", "text": "The FIFA World Cup is the biggest international football tournament. It is held every four years and features national teams from around the world competing for the most prestigious trophy in football."},
    {"id": "c11", "text": "The UEFA European Championship, also called the Euros, is the main international tournament for European national teams. It is held every four years and features many of the world's strongest football nations."},
    {"id": "c12", "text": "Copa America is South America's main international football competition. It includes countries such as Brazil, Argentina, Uruguay, Chile, Colombia, and Peru."},
    {"id": "c13", "text": "The Africa Cup of Nations, also called AFCON, is Africa's main international football tournament. It showcases top African national teams and players from leagues across the world."},
    {"id": "c14", "text": "The Carabao Cup, also known as the EFL Cup, is a domestic knockout competition in English football. It includes clubs from the Premier League and the English Football League."},
    {"id": "c15", "text": "The Community Shield is an annual English match usually played between the Premier League champion and the FA Cup winner. It traditionally acts as the curtain-raiser for the English football season."},
    {"id": "c16", "text": "The Copa del Rey is Spain's main domestic cup competition. It gives clubs from different levels of Spanish football the chance to compete in a knockout format."},
    {"id": "c17", "text": "The DFB-Pokal is Germany's main domestic cup competition. It is known for knockout drama and occasional upsets by lower-division teams."},
    {"id": "c18", "text": "The Coppa Italia is Italy's main domestic cup competition. Serie A clubs often enter in later rounds, and the winner earns domestic silverware and possible European qualification."},


