    {"id": "fc1", "text": "Expected goals, or xG, is a statistic that estimates the quality of a chance based on factors like shot location, angle, body part, and type of assist. A higher xG means the chance was more likely to result in a goal."},
    {"id": "fc2", "text": "Expected assists, or xA, measures the likelihood that a pass will become an assist based on the quality of the chance created. It helps evaluate creative players beyond actual assist totals."},
    {"id": "fc3", "text": "Progressive passes are passes that move the ball significantly closer to the opponent's goal. They are useful for measuring players who advance play rather than simply keeping possession."},
    {"id": "fc4", "text": "Progressive carries are dribbles or ball carries that move the ball significantly closer to goal. They show how players break lines by running with the ball."},
    {"id": "fc5", "text": "Press resistance is a player's ability to keep the ball under pressure. Midfielders with good press resistance use body positioning, close control, and awareness to escape opponents."},
    {"id": "fc6", "text": "Line-breaking passes are passes that bypass one or more defensive lines. They are valuable because they move the ball into more dangerous areas and disrupt the opponent's structure."},
    {"id": "fc7", "text": "Chance creation refers to actions that lead to shots, such as key passes, crosses, through balls, cutbacks, and set-piece deliveries."},
    {"id": "fc8", "text": "A clean sheet means a team has prevented the opponent from scoring during a match. Goalkeepers and defenders are often judged partly by clean sheets."},
    {"id": "fc9", "text": "A brace means a player has scored two goals in a single match. A hat-trick means a player has scored three goals in one match."},
    {"id": "fc10", "text": "A derby is a match between rival teams, usually from the same city or region. Examples include the Manchester Derby, North London Derby, Merseyside Derby, and Madrid Derby."},
    {"id": "fc11", "text": "The number 10 role traditionally refers to a creative attacking midfielder who plays between midfield and attack. This player is responsible for chance creation, final passes, and linking play."},
    {"id": "fc12", "text": "The number 6 role usually refers to a defensive midfielder who protects the back line, wins the ball, and helps progress possession from deep areas."},
    {"id": "fc13", "text": "The number 8 role usually refers to a central midfielder who contributes to both attack and defense. Number 8s often press, carry the ball, combine with attackers, and make late runs."},
    {"id": "fc14", "text": "A through ball is a pass played into space behind the defensive line for an attacker to run onto. It is commonly used against high defensive lines."},
    {"id": "fc15", "text": "A cutback is a pass from near the byline back toward the penalty spot or edge of the box. Cutbacks are dangerous because defenders often run toward their own goal and attackers arrive facing goal."},
    {"id": "fc16", "text": "A high defensive line means defenders position themselves far up the pitch. It helps compress space and support pressing but can be vulnerable to fast attackers running in behind."},
    {"id": "fc17", "text": "A transition is the moment when possession changes from one team to the other. Attacking transitions happen after winning the ball, while defensive transitions happen after losing it."},
    {"id": "fc18", "text": "A second ball is the loose ball after an aerial duel, clearance, or tackle. Winning second balls is important for controlling territory and sustaining attacks."},
    {"id": "fc19", "text": "A duel is a contest between two players for the ball. Duels can be aerial, ground-based, physical, or technical."},
